After checking out Queen's English's Chinese New Year Market, we were getting thirsty and hungry so I recommended going to Red Rocks Pizzeria since I used to frequent their Arlington and Alexandria locations and had fond memories there. They currently offer indoor and outdoor seating. I asked our server for recommendations on fruity cocktails and she recommended either the Pomegranate Martini or Blood Orange Margarita. I chose the latter, which consisted of tequila, lime, cointreau, and blood orange purée shaken, served over the rocks in a salt rimmed glass, and garnished with an orange wedge. We shared an Ananas Pizza, which consisted of pizza dough topped with tomato sauce, mozzarella, crispy prosciutto, and pineapple. I liked how the crust was crispy and airy and the pizza was light, sweet, and savory. It was a great snack!

I ordered a few pizzas to celebrate my wife’s birthday from RedRocks.   The pizza turned out to be greasy and dry and even worse, my debit card number was stolen.  Someone used my card to try to withdraw cash using my debit card number.  Now, I’m still dealing with my bank trying to settle the issues.  When I spoke to the manager at Red Rocks, he was in denial.  I’m trying to give a local restaurant business during the pandemic, and I feel disillusioned and punished for my good will.

My husband and I went there for the first time yesterday. It was nice to sit outside and overall was an okay experience, but I don't know that we'd go back. The servers were nice, and his cocktail was good, and my pizza was SO close to being amazing...The crust and sauce were great. (I got the margherita pizza.) The mozzarella cheese, however, either tasted like some blue cheese got mixed in, or like the cheese was starting to turn. I then made the mistake of asking for a side of marinara for my crust (I like to dip it). The tomato sauce on the pizza was great; I should have asked for that. The marinara, however, was terrible.  Also, the castelvetrano olives come served warm with lemon zest. Some people love that and others don't (my husband unfortuantely wasn't thrilled) so just FYI for anyone that doesn't want to be surprised by that!  His mozzarella tomato basil panini was also just ok. Overall we just weren't thrilled with the food. But that was just our experience. ---------------------------------------------- (EDIT, as to respond to owner): I appreciate the response. I *really* hate complaining at restaurants because it makes me extremely anxious, and we only do if the offence is egregious because we feel the the blame and upset goes onto the servers who don't deserve it. We also really hate to waste food. Not sure what happened with the cheese, but the rest of the pizza was very good. And perhaps we just have different standards for marinara sauce. But thank you for the reply, and maybe we'll try Red Rocks again sometime.

I enjoyed the garlic knots and the calzone here at Red Rocks. The Funghi pizza, however, was not good. The first thing I noticed when it came to our table was the strong smell. I thought it was the mushrooms, but maybe it was the cheese? There was too much oil swimming around on top of this pizza, so much so that the thin crust became soggy. What's most disappointing though, was the flavor. You'd think that with all that was going on with toppings, the flavor at least would be tasty. But no, the pizza fell flat. The only parts that were tasty were where there was caramelized onions. Other bites just tasted so... plain. Overall, decent lunch experience but probably wouldn't make the effort to come here again.

Pizza arrived while we were still working on the appetizer - that's excusable, but the server never bothered to return to clear the appetizer plates. Water was not refilled. Getting the check was a lengthy ordeal and paying another.

There's no shortage of decent pizza in DC, making for steep competition.  RedRocks stacks up pretty well, and fits right in with its neighboring businesses.  The pizza is creative without being unapproachable, and they are accommodating to most requests.  The sauce is house made and worth it -- and keeping up with the rest of DC pizzerias, they keep an excellent bar.  This is a highlight in Columbia Heights.
